Over the weekend, [you were asked to reflect](https://gamvzw.clicks.mlsend.com/td/c/eyJ2Ijoie1wiYVwiOjUyODU2NixcImxcIjoxNzMzODIwNzY0MDY0MzI5NTIsXCJyXCI6MTczMzgyMTMxMjg5OTQ5NjQ3fSIsInMiOiI5Yzc1MmY4YzVkMWJkNWIzIn0) on where you experienced the most challenges in the context of [[DecisionOps]]. The most popular responses appeared to be [[observability]] and [[collaboration]], with some callouts for:

- Managing model versions
    
- Quickly running a model and reviewing the output
    
- Sharing the output with stakeholders via a web app
    
- Reproducing runs and tracking I/O
    

Addressing these challenges successfully is something you can solve Day 1 by applying a little structure to your local development. Without it, you find yourself asking these questions:

- What input did I use to produce that result?
    
- Which output did I send to my colleague for comparison?
    
- Did I just overwrite my run results?
    
- Where did that bar chart PNG get saved…?
    

If you have a good structure for logging your steps and capturing your results, your path to production becomes more straightforward and reliable.

That input for your last run: Stored in a directory logged with a unique name and metadata. That output you sent to your colleague: Housed in the same place. You didn’t overwrite your recent run. Phew! And your bar chart PNG is sitting with all your other run data in a nicely named folder. (Nothing is lost to the netherworld of your Desktop!)

## So long, experiment-5-final-final(2).json

ABC Financial is depending on you to go from local development to prototype to production and beyond smoothly and systematically. And you’re going to deliver. Starting with a good structure for local development.

What is a good starting structure?

Nextmv has developed and open sourced a turnkey organizational structure as part of the [Nextmv Python SDK](https://gamvzw.clicks.mlsend.com/td/c/eyJ2Ijoie1wiYVwiOjUyODU2NixcImxcIjoxNzMzODIwNzY0MDk1Nzg2ODEsXCJyXCI6MTczMzgyMTMxMjg5OTQ5NjQ3fSIsInMiOiIyYWQ4NjRjZmY2MjljNmJlIn0). It helps make [[reproducibility]] and [[referenceability]] effortless.

[Every run you make has a unique run ID and directory](https://gamvzw.clicks.mlsend.com/td/c/eyJ2Ijoie1wiYVwiOjUyODU2NixcImxcIjoxNzMzODIwNzY0MTM3NzI5ODYsXCJyXCI6MTczMzgyMTMxMjg5OTQ5NjQ3fSIsInMiOiJhMDc3MTViMmMyY2ZhZTJkIn0) that houses the run input, output, model metrics you’ve defined, logs, and visual assets. It looks like this:

  

![](data:image/png;base64,)

  

Isn't that nice? Can you feel the wave of calm? Observability unlocked ![✅](data:image/png;base64,)

Minimizing the mega-email thread madness

You will get organized locally, but you're also going to fix inefficient collaboration practices. No more attaching output or log files or PNGs to a message on an email thread 52-replies deep. That practice is just as cringeworthy and inefficient as circulating a Word Doc attachment for co-author review. There's a better way.

With the structure you apply via Nextmv's open source package, you're going to sync your local run data to a free Nextmv account and access the goodness of the Nextmv UI for stakeholder collaboration. It'll look a bit like this:

![](data:image/png;base64,)

Once it's there, sharing the output or error logs or colorful bar chart is as easy as copy-pasting a link and sharing it. And all the context is there. Collaboration unlocked ![✅](data:image/png;base64,)

So let's do this thing. Hop to it!
